Background

We have explored how various U.S. economic indicators are related to each other, which is a classic application for the VAR modeling. In this problem, we will study the inter-dependence and Granger causality between various economic indicators.

Instructions on reading the data

To read the data in R, save the file in your working directory (make sure you have changed the directory if different from the R working directory) and read the data using the R function read.csv()

Question 1a

Plot the time series of all indicators for comparison and discuss whether you find any similarities in terms of trend or other features. Plot also the 1st order difference plots and the corresponding ACF plots. Interpret in terms of stationarity and volatility.

# transform into time series
gdp.ts <- xts(data$GDP, date.quarter)
expgs.ts <- xts(data$EXPGS, date.quarter)
imgpgsc.ts <- xts(data$IMPGSC1, date.quarter)

pce.ts <- xts(data2$PCE, date.month)

# merge into multivariate time series
ts.merge <- merge(gdp.ts, expgs.ts, join = 'inner')
ts.merge <- merge(ts.merge, imgpgsc.ts, join = 'inner')
ts.merge <- merge(ts.merge, unrate.ts, join = 'inner')
ts.merge <- merge(ts.merge, pce.ts, join = 'inner')

# Time series

plot(imgpgsc.ts, xlab="time",main="imgpsc",type="l", col="red")
plot(unrate.ts, xlab="time",main="unrate",type="l", col="blue")
plot(pce.ts, xlab="time",main="pce",type="l", col="orange")

Response Based on timeseries plots, we can clearly see an increasing trend in all but unrate timeseries.Unrate timeseries shows some cyclic ups and downs. Additionally, ACF plots of time series shows clear trend as all values are higher than the treshold. these are indications of non-stationarity of the time series.We see non-constant (volatility) towards the end of each time series more pronoounced than that in the begining of the time.

The 1st order differenced timeseries plots clearly shows improvemennt inn trend with constant mean up until the very ennd of the timeline. All these plots shows very high change in mean and variance at the end of timeline. Variance is also constant again up until the very en of the timeline. there are only one high ACF values that are higher than the threshold in each differenced timeseries acf plots of pce and expgs. 1st order timeseries are much closer to be stationary with very minimal volatility.

Divide the GDP data into training data including the data for years 1959 to 2020 with the last two quarters being the testing data. Fit the trend using the splines regression to the GDP training time series and apply ARMA to the residuals. Evaluate goodness of fit for the ARMA model. Forecast the first two quarters of 2021 (testing data) and compare to the observed one. Discuss why there are (or not!) significant differences between predicted vs observed.

time.pts = c(1:length(gdp.ts))

gdp.gam.fit = gam(gdp_train~s(time))

## Order selection -- AIC 
n_r = length(gdp.gam.resid)
n_r
## [1] 248
norder = 6
p = c(1:norder)-1; q = c(1:norder)-1
aic = matrix(0,norder,norder)
for(i in 1:norder){
  for(j in 1:norder){
    modij = arima(gdp.gam.resid,order = c(p[i],0,q[j]), method='ML')
    aic[i,j] = modij$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*n_r/(n_r-p[i]-q[j]-2)
  }  
}

aicv = as.vector(aic)  
#plot(aicv,ylab="AIC values")
indexp = rep(c(1:norder),norder)
indexq = rep(c(1:norder),each=norder)
indexaic = which(aicv == min(aicv))
porder = indexp[indexaic]-1
qorder = indexq[indexaic]-1

print(c('porder: ', porder))
## [1] "porder: " "4"
print(c('qorder: ', qorder))
## [1] "qorder: " "3"
## Fit ARMA Model
final_model.1 = arima(gdp.gam.resid,order = c(porder,0,qorder), method='ML')
resids.1 = resid(final_model.1)
## Residual Analysis
par (mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(resids.1, ylab='Standardized Residuals')
abline(h=0)
acf(resids.1,main= 'ACF of the Model Residuals')
pacf(resids.1,main='PACF of the Model Residuals')
qqnorm(resids.1)
qqline(resids.1)

## Order selection -- AIC for ARIMA
norder = 6
p = c(1:norder)-1; q = c(1:norder)-1
aic = matrix(0,norder,norder)
for(i in 1:norder){
  for(j in 1:norder){
    modij = arima(gdp_train,order = c(p[i],1,q[j]), method='ML')
    aic[i,j] = modij$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*n/(n-p[i]-q[j]-2)
  }  
}

aicv = as.vector(aic)  
#plot(aicv,ylab="AIC values")

Response from VAR selection method, it was found that p for AIC (8) is larger than p for BIC (2). Based on Wald test, expgs, imqpsc and pce do Granger-cause pdp since p values are less than 0.05 therefore we reject the null hypothesis that all coefficients on lagged values of these time series arer zero. However, for unrate the p value is > 0.05 so we cannot reject the null hypothesis.

Question 4: Reflection

From what you encountered above and your conceptual understanding of VAR modelling, reflect on the relative strengths and weaknesses of the modelling approach. Particularly, you will need to put this analysis into the perspective of the impact of the covid-19 pandemic on GDP.

Response

In general, it is very difficult to pin point the causality of one in a very complex system. The variables used to estimate for gdp in last ten years may have been changed in last year due to very unexpected changes occured during covid pandemic. Old assumptions may or may not still be valid. Additionally, after covid a new dynamic in economy may occur therefore it would also be very difficult to predict the changes right away as we need to establish new norm first.
